vectorData.altText: That's right!  The posterior cord is formed by the union of all 3 posterior divisions.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Continuing distally, confirm that each of the three trunks bifurcate to form divisions, designated anterior and posterior. 
Identify the posterior cord and confirm that it is formed by the union of the three posterior divisions. The posterior cord gives rise to a nerve that is contained within the posterior compartments of the arm and forearm. 
Follow the anterior divisions of the superior and middle trunks to where the unite to form the lateral cord. Confirm that the anterior division of the inferior trunk continues as the medial cord. The lateral and medial cords, formed from the anterior divisions, give rise to nerves contained within the anterior compartments of the arm and forearm.

START in the neck, and identify the roots of the brachial plexus,
Remember, these contain fibres associated with a single spinal level.

Confirm that the following now makes sense to you: The superior trunk contains fibres from C5 and C6, the middle trunk contains fibres from C7 only, and the inferior trunk contains fibres from C8 and T1.
